John Edwards: Language skills are essential for the world’s citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding test results, reinforced by personal and group success in sports, art, music and other areas of community practice.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further and higher education, for the careers they choose and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector able to design and implement a personalized curriculum, we find that modern languages continue to gain popularity as a sought-after field of study in school.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it gets into his head.
If you talk to a man in his own language, it goes to his heart.”
This is an important reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of the most recent tests this year, it can be seen that languages are at the top of the tables with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a high A.
Data collected from 74 schools that are members of SCIS showed that 72 percent of students scored high in Mandarin, as did 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish.
These data show that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and youth will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today the field of languages as a subject of choice is considered at the same level as STEM subjects (Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the British Council for Employment and Skills found that among the reasons employers cited codes for filling vacancies, 17 per cent were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Thus, increasingly, language skills become essential to prepare students for future careers.
In view of the increase in language requirements for future job opportunities, these skills are essential in a world of globalization.
No matter what career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a significant advantage in the future due to this lifelong ability.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically stabilizes a person in an advantageous position over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 per cent could not speak a foreign language at a level sufficient for conversation, and French was the only language with a double-digit number of speakers, 15 per cent.
This is why it is important to invest in language education for children.
Knowledge of many languages, especially those of developing countries, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
Within Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages taught.
Some schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will learn languages considered most important to Britain in the 20th century, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever your child’s field of interest, there will always be a variety of languages to choose from in independent schools, with a team of teachers specializing in the field.
Independent schools in Scotland are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, in any foreseeable future.
It is undeniable today, in a global business environment, that languages continue to be of vital importance to the future of the country, so this fact should be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be regarded as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer these levels of choice, diversity and excellence to the children of Scotland.
It's the order of the hour.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council for Independent Schools.
