Update on Red Tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manati and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Wildlife and Fish Commission shows a general decline in red tide concentrations in some parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more diffuse flowering conditions have been reported in the provinces of Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, indicating decreasing concentrations.
The red tide blooms over 130 miles from the coast, from the northern province of Pinellas to the southern province of Lee.
The plots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but at a smaller number of locations compared to last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Median concentrations at the coast or off the coast of the province of Pinellas were reported last week, low to medium concentrations at the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations at Manatee County, background to high concentrations at the coast or off the coast of Sarasota County.
There are ongoing reports of respiratory stimuli from Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory stimuli have been reported in northwestern Florida over the past week.
